Childless couples to get IVF on the NHS after two years instead of three: new guidance
Childless couples will only have to try to conceive for two years before receiving IVF on the NHS, the health service rationing body has said, as fertility treatment is extended to gay couples and women over 40. A standard cycle of IVF treatment can cost between £3,00 and £8,000 Photo: Alamy	By Rebecca Smith, Medical Editor
7:00AM GMT 20 Feb 2013
Comments
In the biggest shake-up of fertility guidelines in almost ten years, the National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence, has recommended more people are given fertility treatment on the NHS. Women aged up to 42 will qualify for NHS funded treatment under certain circumstances, along with same sex couples and those with physical disability that make natural conception difficult. The length of time couples will have to try to conceive naturally has been reduced from three years to two, in order to boost their chances of success. Where there is a known fertility problems, couples can be referred immediately for treatment, where as previously they would have to wait up to three years under previous guidance despite knowing their chances of natural conception were almost nil. The guidelines were welcomed by fertility doctors and patients groups, however some warned that because the recommendations were not binding, commissioners may choose to ignore them or stipulate their own restrictions in order to keep costs down. Related Articles
