09 May 2013
Couple make medical history with birth of quadruplet girls
15 May 2013
Scottish women over 40 to get IVF on the NHS
16 May 2013
More IVF for gay and older couples
16 Feb 2013
Drugs used to boost the chances of a baby are causing a rise in multiple pregnancies: experts
07 Feb 2013
Fertility treatment waiting times halve after increased payments to donors
26 Nov 2012
A standard cycle of IVF treatment can cost between £3,00 and £8,000. In 2011, four in ten of the 61,000 IVF cycles carried out in Britain were funded by the NHS, which would increase to 93 per cent of cycles if the new guidance were fully implemented. £60.5m on fertility treatment. THe NHS in England currently spends around £60.4m because the original 2004 guidance is not fully implemented everywhere. If the new guideline is fully implemented, it will cost an additional £65.2m, Nice calculated. Some recommendations will save the NHS money including stricter criteria for the use of one embryo at a time in order to reduce the number of twins and triplets born following IVF, and reductions in the use of less effective treatments such as artificial insemination and stimulation drugs. Women aged 23 to 39 will still qualify for three full cycles of IVF on the NHS and now in addition, women aged 40 to 42 will be eligible for one full cycle under certain circumstances. Dr Tim Child, consultant gynaecologist and director of the Oxford Fertility Unit, who helped draw up the guidelines, said: "It is very clear in my daily work that people get stuck at various stages in the system and as time moves on their chances of success both naturally and with assisted conception techniques only goes down. "The 2004 guideline said couples should try naturally for three years which was really too long to make couples wait before moving on to an effective treatment such as IVF. With the new recommendation of two years the outcome will be to prevent people waiting an extra year when their success rate only reduces." Some experts were concerned that due to the financial problems in the NHS the guidelines would not be fully implemented. British Fertility Society spokesman, Dr Sue Avery said: "It is now almost ten years since Nice first published guidelines on fertility treatment and we are still in the untenable position that the majority of Primary Care Trusts have not fully implemented these and patients in many areas of the country are unable to access treatment. "Being denied appropriate fertility treatment can have a devastating consequence on patients’ lives, effectively denying them the right to a family." Clare Lewis-Jones, chief executive of the patient group Infertility Network UK, said that only one in four primary care trusts provide the three full cycles as stipulated in the 2004 guideline, two PCTs do not fund any fertility treatment and the rest fund one or two cycles. Many PCTs place their own 'social criteria' on funding, including denying IVF to a woman whose partner has children from a previous relationship, denying funding to smokers or those with body mass index over a set point. Mrs Lewis-Jones said: “Let’s not forget that infertility is a medical condition and that people with a fertility problem have the same right to be treated by the NHS as anyone else. "It is now nearly 10 years since the guideline was first published yet sadly we are still facing an arbitrary approach to IVF funding around the country. “We know the current system leaves many people unable to access NHS treatment and we need reassurance about the future of NHS fertility treatment as we move towards GP commissioning in 2013." Health News
