Just back: along the Gin Drinker's Line
Paul Bingley wins this week's Just Back travel writing competition for this account of a delve into the past of the Hong Kong New Territories. Dusk on the MacLehose hiking trail in the Hong Kong New Territories Photo: Alamy	<
>
More travel competitions
Email your entry to the Just Back competition
Article
The best of Just Back
By Paul Bingley
9:51AM GMT 13 Jan 2012
Comments
'Don’t stare,” whispers Martin. “He’ll want to fight you.” I’m gaping at an angry puce face when two wild hazel eyes swivel in my direction. I quickly look away. I’ve no intention of confronting the macaque. I’m here to see another battle up ahead. We’re climbing scores of steps through Hong Kong’s Shing Mun Country Park. Their route forms part of the MacLehose Trail, a 62-mile pathway lacing together the pine-cloaked peaks of the New Territories. For the moment, the clamour of Hong Kong Island fades away below us. The calm, however, is soon replaced by squeals of terror as a group of schoolgirls turns and runs after failing to outstare the macaque. “Poor blighter,” sighs Martin. “He gets no peace.”
Peace has been a rare commodity in Shing Mun. Seventy years ago, it lost its serenity to commotion when British and Commonwealth soldiers attempted to fight off a Japanese assault on its hillsides. Subsequently, on December 25 1941, Hong Kong surrendered. Over the next four years, the British colony came under a very different type of foreign administration. Shing Mun suffered in the process. Post-invasion, vast swathes were cut down by the Japanese. Today, Hong Kong’s Country & Marine Parks Authority has replenished its five and a half square miles of Chinese pines. But there still remains a thin streak of bare earth that is faithfully kept as it was by a small group of volunteers, including Martin. He’s keen to show me, so we veer off the path and clamber beneath the splayed legs of an electricity pylon. “Welcome to the Gin Drinker’s Line!”
