This bald crest forms part of the “Oriental Maginot”, a defensive line conceived by the British to protect Hong Kong’s northern approaches. Built during the Thirties and named after a former bay, the 11-mile string of trenches and bunkers housed up to 2,500 men. It boasted a redoubt, headquarters, and was linked by a series of tunnels. Lowering himself into one, Martin beckons me down. He disappears through a cloud of dust and I follow. We descend a steep rectangular passageway before Martin abruptly halts. “Did you know that the London Underground had an overseas branch?” Pointing to the concrete wall, Martin nods at a perfectly chiselled arrow pointing the way to Piccadilly. Below that, another one leads off towards Charing Cross. “Who needs the Bakerloo Line when you’re on the Gin Drinker’s, eh?”
The British had named its defensive positions after London landmarks in the hope of helping the troops acclimatise to their far-flung battle stations. The ploy failed to work; the Gin Drinker’s Line collapsed in less than one day. This is illustrated at the shrapnel-scarred exit from Strand Palace Hotel, where Japanese engravings declare the bunker “captured by the Kobayashi Detachment”. As I escape its dank confines, I spot some macaques eyeing me warily. I tread peacefully, but realise we’ve invaded their territory again. Enter the next round
